{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{infobox organization | name = Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society | image = | image_border = | size = 150 | map = | msize = | mcaption = | alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | formation = 1866 | type = [[Historical society]] | status = Charity | registration_id = 227786 | purpose = Historical study and research | headquarters = United Kingdom | leader_title = Activities | leader_name = Research and publications, lectures and events | leader_title2 = Collections | leader_name2 = Library, archives | leader_title3 = Patrons | leader_name3 = Rt Rev. [[James Newcome]], [[Bishop of Carlisle]], Claire Hensman, [[Lord Lieutenant of Cumbria]] | leader_title4 = President | leader_name4 = Dr Rob David | website = [http://www.cumbriapast.com/cgi-bin/ms/main.pl?action=home www.cumbriapast.com] }}
The '''Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society''', founded in 1866, is a [[English local history|local historical]], [[antiquarian]], [[archaeology|archaeological]] and [[text publication society]] and [[registered charity]] covering the modern county of [[Cumbria]].
==Aims== The society exists to "promote, encourage, foster" the combined studies of [[genealogy]], history, [[Tradition|custom]] and [[archaeology]], within the boundaries of the [[non-metropolitan county]] of [[Cumbria]] (which, as well as the two titular [[Historic counties of England|historic counties]] of [[Cumberland]] and [[Westmorland]], includes elements of historic [[Yorkshire]] and [[Lancashire]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cumbriapast.com/ms/pdf/Society_constitution_Apr_16.pdf |title= Revised Rules, 2008 and 2012 |publisher=Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society |accessdate=21 May 2016 }}</ref>
==History== The society was established in [[Penrith, Cumbria]] on 11 September 1866, with "five business and professional men from both counties" as founder-members.<ref name=Gazette>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Thomas |url=http://www.thewestmorlandgazette.co.uk/news/14259669.NOSTALGIA__Society_aimed_to_preserve_the_antiquities_of_two_counties/?ref=mac |title=Nostalgia: Society aimed to preserve the antiquities of two counties |newspaper=[[The Westmorland Gazette]] |date=7 February 2016 }}</ref> The then [[Hugh Lowther, 5th Earl of Lonsdale|Earl of Lonsdale]] was appointed honorary president. One of the society's first official acts was to campaign for the protection of the [[Dunmail Raise]] [[cairn]], and to organise an [[archaeological dig]] on the [[Borrowdale|Low Borrow Bridge]] [[Roman fort]], near [[Tebay]]. Membership rose to 115 by 1866 (with around a quarter being clergymen), and "includ[ed] three ladies".<ref name=Gazette/> The society returned to the Low Borrow Bridge site, by then a [[scheduled monument]], in 2011 and discovered further evidence as to the size of the camp,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cumbria-14362255 |title=Archaeologists excavate Roman fort near Tebay |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=9 August 2011 }}</ref> while in 2015 it was a joint funder of work into a [[dendrochronological]] [[Dating methodologies in archaeology|dating]] on [[Kendal]]'s fourteenth-century [[The Castle Dairy|Castle dairy]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Carl |last=Fallowfield |url=http://www.cumbriacrack.com/2015/04/29/fascinating-finds-shed-light-on-history-of-ancient-dairy/ |title=Fascinating finds shed light on history of ancient dairy |website=Cumbria Crack |date=29 April 2015 }}</ref>
==Publications== A publishing arm was created in 1877,<ref name=Gazette/> and by 2015 was responsible for publishing its [[peer-review]]ed journal ''The Transactions'' of the society, a triannual [[newsletter]], and various dedicated book series for specific areas of interest (for example, the Extra Series, and those for Records, Research, and Tracts).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cumbriapast.com/cgi-bin/ms/main.pl?action=editorial |title=Publications Committee |website=Cumbria Past |publisher=Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society |accessdate=21 May 2016 }}</ref>
===Select publications=== *Mullett, M.A., ''Patronage, Power and Politics in Appleby in the Era of Lady Anne Clifford 1649–1689'', 2015. *Zant, J., ''Penrith: the Historic Core'', 2015. *Brennand, M. & Stringer, K.J. (Eds), ''The Making of Carlisle: from Romans to Railways'', 2011. *Cherry, P., ''Studies in Northern Prehistory '', 2007. *Austin, P.S., ''Bewcastle and Old Penrith '', 1991.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cumbriapast.com/cgi-bin/ms/main.pl?action=publications&pub_id=85&archive= |title=Publications available |website=Cumbria Past |publisher=Cumberland and Westmorland Antiquarian and Archaeological Society |accessdate=21 May 2016 }}</ref>
