[[File:J. Collingwood Bruce 1805-1892.jpg|thumb]] The Reverend '''John Collingwood Bruce''', [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London|FSA]] (1805–1892) was an English nonconformist minister and schoolmaster, known as a historian of [[Tyneside]] and author. He co-operated with [[John Stokoe (author)|John Stokoe]] in compiling the major song collection ''[[Northumbrian Minstrelsy]]'' published in 1882<ref name=AllansMisc>{{cite web|title=Allan's Illustrated Edition of Tyneside songs and readings|url=https://archive.org/stream/allansillustrat00firgoog/allansillustrat00firgoog_djvu.txt}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Allan's Illustrated Edition of Tyneside songs and readings with lives, portraits and autographs of the writers, and notes on the songs. Revised Edition|year=1891|publisher=Thomas & Gorge Allan, 18 Blackett Street, and 34 Collingwood Street, (Newcastle upon Tyne) – Sold by W. Allan, 80 Grainqer Street, Newcastle upon Tyne, B. Allan, North Shields and Walter Scott. London}}</ref>
== Early life == The eldest son of John Bruce of [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], he was educated at the Percy Street Academy, a well-known school in Newcastle kept by his father, and afterwards at [[Mill Hill School]], Middlesex. He entered [[Glasgow University]] in 1821, graduated M.A. in 1826, and became hon. LL.D. in 1853.
In early life, Bruce studied for the [[Presbyterian]] ministry, but never sought a call from any congregation. In 1831, he began to assist in the management of his father's school, of which he became sole proprietor in 1834, when his father died. He retired from the school, after a successful career, in 1863.{{sfn|Wroth|1901}}
== Historical interests ==
Bruce's main interest was in the history of Britain, in particular [[North East England]] and more specifically [[Roman Britain]] and [[Hadrian's Wall]]. His books used a numbering system for the structures of the Wall, and by about 1930 it had become standard, using the [[milecastle]] located to the east. Examples are T33a or Turret 26B (Brunton): (see [[Turret (Hadrian's Wall)#Numbering system and naming|Numbering system and naming]]. His interest in music was largely historical, and in editing the ''Northumbrian Minstrelsy'' he co-operated with John Stokoe .
The article [[Music of Northumbria]] credits Stokoe with copying out, in 1850, some of the tunes from John Smith's tunebook of 1750, a book now long lost, and the pair creating this comprehensive collection of old Northern Songs. The work was on behalf of, and published by, the Ancient Melodies Committee of the [[Society of Antiquaries of Newcastle upon Tyne]], of which Bruce was an active committee member.
Bruce gave the [[Rhind Lectures]] in 1883, on the Roman occupation of Britain.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}
== Family == His father, also John, had been a schoolteacher for over 40 years, first in [[Alnwick]], then in [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]]. He was an author and had written books, including a work on Geography. He died at his home in Percy Street, Newcastle on 31 October 1834 aged 60 years. <ref>{{cite web|title= Thomas Fordyce's Local records : or, Historical register of remarkable events".|url=https://archive.org/stream/localrecordsorhi03sykeuoft/localrecordsorhi03sykeuoft_djvu.txt|quote=This information is taken from Local Records for this day in [[W & T Fordyce (publishers)|Thomas Fordyce]]'s "Local records : or, Historical register of remarkable events }}</ref>
Bruce married in 1833 Charlotte, daughter of T. Gainsford of Gerrard's Cross, [[Buckinghamshire]], and had two sons and two daughters. The eldest son. Sir [[Gainsford Bruce]], became one of the judges of the [[High Court of Justice]].{{sfn|Wroth|1901}}
== Death == John Collingwood Bruce died on 5 April 1892; his wife Charlotte died in 1893, and their daughter Frances died aged 18 months on 17 December 1839. They are buried in the family grave in [[Jesmond Old Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Friends of Jesmond Old Cemetery|url= http://www.jesmondoldcemetery.co.uk/history_2.html}}</ref> Other children include [[Gainsford Bruce|Sir Gainsford Bruce]].
A photograph of the headstone can be seen – <ref>{{cite web|title= Bruce family grave|url= http://www.fototime.com/19D7A2CAB37917F/orig.jpg}}</ref> (courtesy of Steve Ellwood, [[Whitley Bay]]).
A sculptured marble sarcophagus within [[Newcastle Cathedral|St Nicholas' Cathedral]] shows the carved body of J. C. Bruce lying with his feet on a copy of his book ''Hadrian's Wall''.<ref>{{cite web|title= Marble statue of Bruce in St Nicholas' Cathedral courtesy of Steve Ellwood |url= http://www.fototime.com/D7485C4B2D33363/orig.jpg}}</ref>
== Selected works ==
=== Music === * ''[[Northumbrian Minstrelsy|Northumbrian Minstrelsy. A collection of Ballads, Melodies and Small Pipe Tunes of Northumbria]]'' (206 pages) – edited by John Collingwood Bruce and John Stokoe – published 1882.<ref>{{cite web|title= Northumbrian Minstrelsy by Bruce and Stokoe, 1882|url= https://archive.org/details/ACollectionOfTheBalladsMelodiesAndSmall-pipeTunesOfNorthumbria}}</ref>
The article [[Music of Northumbria]], credits [[John Stokoe (author)|John Stokoe]] with copying out, in 1850, some of the tunes from John Smith's tunebook of 1750, a book now long lost, and, together with John Collingwood Bruce, creating this comprehensive collection of old Northern Songs. The work was on behalf of, and published by, the Ancient Melodies Committee of the [[Society of Antiquaries of Newcastle upon Tyne]].
